In article &lt;1588@edison.GE.COM&gt; rja@edison.GE.COM (rja) writes:
&gt;
&gt;  I'll just say that I'm rather less than comfortable with the increasing
&gt;use of "pseudo-domains."  I'm very much in favor of the domain system and

Me too. Domains are a clever way of sorting addresses. One of
their strengths is that they are divorced from the physical
region of the site.  That is not always useful.

If the three letter codes used by the airlines were reserved for
geographic regions corresponding to the airport service area we
may be able to build useful 'local' and 'regional' networks and
routing.  Since these codes are already standard something might
come of it.

Mailers then could attempt to just get it close and let some
other machine modify the address for final delivery.  I expect
half of the long distance UUCP mail makes two crossings.  One
long distance call is to the domain then back with a real
destination.

This could be a big cost advantage to all large domains (except
AT&amp;T).

Opinions??

Examples:

RNO -- Reno Intl. Airport would identify the Reno northern Nevada
	area. My address might be  "mitch@stride1.stride.COM.RNO"

ERK -- Newark Airport for Northern New Jersey

LAX -- Los Angeles.

NOTE: Why not AT&amp;T you ask.  Well they are the phone company.

Start in LA for a message 
	To: joeuser@amachine.ATT.COM
You pay the bill from LA to New Jersey they make enough to
pass it back to a machine in Los Angeles.  Now if the address is 
	To: joeuser@amachine.ATT.COM.LAX
much of the long distance toll could be avoided.

This is a good Idea to reduce the instruction set of uucp routing So:
